            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Sharma\u2019s name has always been a conversation starter. Born in Sacramento to an Indian immigrant father, a pragmatic software engineer, and a White American mother, a high school history teacher from Oregon, David\u2019s upbringing was a blend of two distinct worlds. While his father, Ravi, instilled in him a respect for logic and hard work, his mother, Susan, nurtured his communication skills and a broader, more humanistic worldview. He identifies as White, having grown up firmly in the orbit of his mother\u2019s American culture, yet the surname Sharma has always connected him to a heritage he felt at a slight remove from.\n\nHis educational journey was a deliberate construction. After earning an Economics degree from UC Davis, he worked for three years at a B2B software company in the Bay Area. There, he saw a clear ceiling. The real architects of the business were not the grinders, but the visionaries with elite credentials. This realization was his key turning point. He dedicated himself to his GMATs and was accepted into UCLA\u2019s MBA program, a two-year crucible that refined his ambition and gave him a network.\n\nNow 31, David is a Senior Product Manager at a thriving fintech company in SoMa. His life is a study in curated efficiency. He lives in a sleek Hayes Valley one-bedroom, a neighborhood he chose for its walkability and proximity to both culture and his company\u2019s shuttle stop. His days are a marathon of meetings, roadmap planning, and navigating the treacherous currents between engineering, design, and market demands. He earns a comfortable $215,000, yet the San Francisco dream of homeownership still feels like a distant aspiration.\n\nHis social life is centered on a tight-knit group of friends from his MBA program and old colleagues. They are his urban family, sharing weekend hikes in Marin, exploring new restaurants, and commiserating over the city\u2019s absurd dating scene. He\u2019s been seeing a graphic designer named Chloe, but it\u2019s still in that fragile, undefined early stage. David\u2019s ultimate hope is to become a Director of Product within three years, and perhaps, one day, cash in his stock options to fund a smaller, less soul-crushing venture of his own. For now, he rides the pristine shuttle through the complicated city streets, a perfect metaphor for his existence: a comfortable, driven professional moving through a beautiful, chaotic world he\u2019s still trying to make his own."
        },
