            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent glare of the conference room at his first job. He was 25. He\u2019d spent a month modeling data for a new feature, but it was the VP of Product, a Stanford MBA, who presented the work as his own sharp insight. In that moment, watching the effortless way the executive commanded the room, David felt a cold clarity. He wasn\u2019t just underpaid; he was invisible. This wasn't about injustice, it was about strategy. It was the moment he decided to stop being a cog and learn how to build the machine.\n\n2.\nHe was eight, at a parent-teacher conference in Sacramento, sitting beside his mother. Another parent glanced at his name tag, then at his mom\u2019s fair features. \u201cSharma,\u201d the woman said, her head tilted. \u201cAre you\u2026?\u201d The question trailed off, left hanging in the air. David felt himself become a human question mark. It wasn\u2019t malicious, just curious, but it was the first time he understood his name was a story others tried to solve before he even spoke. It silently placed him at an arm\u2019s length from the world he knew.\n\n3.\nThe acceptance email from UCLA arrived at 9 PM on a Tuesday. He was 26, sitting in his dull Sacramento studio, the glow of the laptop screen lighting up his tired face. After a year of relentless GMAT prep and essay writing, the word \u201cCongratulations\u201d seemed to vibrate. It wasn't just joy; it was a profound, seismic relief. It felt like a key turning in a lock he\u2019d been picking for years. For the first time, he felt he was the architect of his own life, not just a passenger.\n\n4.\nAbout a year ago, after a brutal week, he skipped the shuttle and walked home. He found himself in Alamo Square as the fog began its silent creep over the city. He watched the famous Painted Ladies stand against the gleaming towers of the financial district, and the sheer, impossible beauty of it all hit him. The anxiety of his rent, his career, the city's relentless pace\u2014it all receded. He felt a quiet sense of ownership, a feeling that this chaotic, gorgeous place was, in its own way, finally becoming his.\n\n5.\nOn his third date with Chloe, they were walking through the Botanical Garden. He was explaining a complex team dynamic at work, framing it as a strategic challenge. She stopped and gently touched his arm. \"That just sounds really stressful,\" she said, her eyes searching his. \"Are you okay?\" The simple sincerity of it disarmed him completely. He was so used to optimizing and analyzing that he\u2019d forgotten to just feel. It was a tiny crack in his curated armor, reminding him that connection wasn't a problem to be solved."
